title: PrintRite DIY 3D Printer Fan Duct v2

description.text: An update to my fan duct for the PrintRite DIY 3D Printer. It has a larger duct from the fan to the corner to allow less restricted airflow. I have another, better design here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1242620

Print it out on its side as oriented in the STL file, attach to the front surface of the extruder carriage with double-sided foam tape.
Remove the existing extruder fan and move it to the duct. Drill some holes for the fan screws and mount the fan to the duct with some sheet metal screws. Install a new 40mm fan on the Extruder. Run a new pair of wires to supply constant 12V power to the fan on the extruder. I'm pretty sure the Extruder fan should be running all the time to maintain the correct temperature gradient inside the nozzle, not varied as it is from the factory. I also used this 12V constant power to run a section of LED strip under the carriage. It gets dark under there..

comments.text: There is only one "official" fan plug on the board.  Use the wiring coming from it to control as many fans you want to have variable speed (up to a max of 700mA of current draw).  Connect other fans to +12v and ground.  I just wrapped some bare wire around the legs going into the board from the power connector and soldered them on.

title: Diffusion Eq. with Heavside Function Initial Conditions

description.text: This model represents the solution to the diffusion equation with the initial conditions of the Heavside function, H(x). You can think of it like this: Imagine you have a thin metal bar and heat up one side, so that it is uniformly at some temperature, and the other side is uniformly at a cooler temperature. As time passes, the heat will flow from the warm side to the cool side. The position on the bar and time are the two axis, while heat is the height. Since the diffusion equation also governs things like the diffusion of a chemical in water, there are many other possible interpretations. Read more at Wikipedia: https://secure.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/wiki/Diffusion_equation This model was made with one of the predecessors to surfcad. You can read more here: https://christopherolah.wordpress.com/2011/07/16/surface-oriented-cad-math-telescopes/
If you want to make a colored one, I've written a bit about how to do it here: https://christopherolah.wordpress.com/2010/12/08/multi-colour-3d-printing-by-filament-swapping/

This is a "bad apple" picker, not a bad design for an apple picker.  Its designed to pick rotten apples off the trees.  The deer, ground hogs, fox, possum and racoon clean them up pretty quickly and the tree can devote resources to the healthy apples.  
Acetone-ABS slurry weld the two parts and find a long piece of bamboo that is about 1.5 cm at the end.  You can drill a hole in the side and put in a pin but a pressure fit works just fine.  
The "connector" file is for connecting two pieces of bamboo for a longer reach.

title: Ultimaker Original Feet with Silicone Dampener

description.text:
I designed a new foot for the Ultimaker Original. It has a hollow base to pour with two-component silicone. After printing turn it head down, mix around 18 ml silicone and fill it up to the top level. When the silicone is done seperate it with a knife from the outer walls and then remove the frame. The 3 holes are spreading inside so that they tightly hold the silicone. The silicone I use is permanently very soft and the printer swings on it. If it's too soft you can easily just take regular silicone from the shops.   
The feet stick very much on the printer so that you can lift it without falling off. I made them that high on purpose as I'll put the printer  into a stand that I build next. The feet will disappear around 2 cms in a wooden plate then. That plate will have 2 larger PC fans integrated so that the cooling unit of the UMO can be removed completely.   
I printed the feet with Innofil3D White PLA at 80 mm/s with 0.2 mm layer height, 0.8 mm walls and 50% infill to make it strong. Bed temperature was 60°C printed on Kapton-tape with a bit of ABS-acetone-solution.   
I tried to break one of them with my hands with force but couldn't break it. Maybe Chuck Norris is the only one who could. :-)  
You need two of them as attached and two mirrored ones. In CURA select the part on the table, click mirror on the bottom menu and the mirror on X or Y. Print it upright with the hollow base bottom down and use support from the table. It is good if the bottom is not very smooth as the silicone sticks better on it.

title: 20th Century Statue of Liberty Souvenir Model

description.text: Before the rise of resins and plastics in souvenirs, pot metal was a cheap alternative and preferred material for making souvenir model of famous landmarks. The pot metal would be electroplated in copper to simulate a bronze finish after being cast and cleaned. In this particular example, the model of the Statue of Liberty was actually copied from an older example. Not many people would notice but hardcore Statue of Liberty collectors probably have noticed the strikingly similar appearance of this model to that of the first souvenir models of the Statue of Liberty made here in America. The very first models were made in Brooklyn, NY starting around 1884. They were sold to raise funds to build the pedestal for the Statue of Liberty. While they were popular and sold by Macy's and other department stores and in newspaper ads, it ultimately took Joseph Pulitzer and his populist crowdfunding drive to gather enough money during the financial panic of the 1880s to finish the pedestal for Liberty. A careful look at this model comparing it to it's antecedent would reveal that the souvenir company had taken a mold off the original 19th century "American Committee Model" (as it was first known) and had some tweaks and alterations done to it to hide it's origins. The pyramid base under the pedestal was originally smooth-sided with the name of the American Committee and their copyright and trademark in fancy script on the front. The details of the pedestal and goddess were much finer and better sculpted than represented here. In particular her feet were plainly visible with the individual toes, the inscription of July 4 1776 on the tablet, the facial features, the individual rays of the crown were sharp and clean plus her fingers and other details. Unfortunately, making a mold from an existing sculpture or statue usually results in "blurry" details and loss of fidelity. The other thing most noticeable is that an extra layer of masonry was added to the top of the pedestal just under the base of the goddess. In the original model, the pedestal and Liberty came apart easily. They were made in two parts so the pedestal could be nickel-plated while the goddess was electroplated in pure copper to simulate bronze. Then they'd be mated together before being sold. A great photo of an orignal American Committee model can be seen here: https://goo.gl/664DBc

I set this model on a small turn table (or lazy susan as some would call it) near the front windows of my living room that face north on a sunny day. The light was bright but indirect, so there were no hard shadows or blown-out highlights. I ended up snapping about 60 photos in all.   
I then used Agisoft Photoscan to recreate the model on a high setting. I used Meshmixer to scale the STL file to match its real-world counterpart.

description.text:
UPDATE: 5/16" Aluminum bed setup has been fixed in customizer. The operation currently being tested includes the use of the original boss nut. Please do not remove your boss nut unless you are a competent technician capable of repairing any unexpected problems. Make sure your print 2 of these sets before doing any unreversable modifications. This is a design that I came up with after seeing some slight banding still in my prints even after doing the M5 threaded rod upgrade. The idea behind how this works is that we want to let the rod go where it wants to go in the X and Y axis without letting it affect the position of the bed. We do this by encapsulating the nut in a low friction "wobble space". This space allows the nut travel space in the X and Y but not in the Z axis. All this results in little to no movement in the bed even when the threaded rod is slightly bent or off center. Full documentation of this project can be found on the soliforums.
http://www.soliforum.com/topic/2727/fix-zbanding-without-caring-about-backlash-slop-nut/ The 5/16" kit only uses one nut currently. This may be altered in the future but will required longer hardware to accomodate. All the current files use the stock solidoodle hardware for mounting. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oOce33y1E44

Use the customizer to select with bed you have and what size rod you are going to use this for. http://www.soliforum.com/topic/2727/fix-zbanding-without-caring-about-backlash-slop-nut/ Please view the forums for full instructions.

description.text:
After looking at the Mars Exploration Rover: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10057 I was inspired to do something in OpenScad that I've wanted to do for a long time. This thing is a technique for representing and rendering your models using some arrays and 'recursion'. There are just a couple of routines introduced, but with them, you can essentially do something like: CSG([OP_UNION, [
[PRIM_CYLINDER, [2,2, 8+15+3],zero(), zero()],
[PRIM_CYLINDER, [4,4, 3],zero(),zero()],
]]); or, if you just want to do a simple part;
place_prim([PRIM_CYLINDER, [2,2, 8+15+3],zero(), zero()]); This is not earth shattering, but it's just another tool in the text modeling arsenal. Since the models, as well as the operations on parts, are simply represented as arrays of numbers, you can use functions to generate these, or concatenations of them. It's kind of interesting in that the code begins to look like LISP or other array based variants. At any rate, it's another technique. The openscad_vm.scad file contains the actual brains. There is a 'test_openscad_vm.scad' file that shows some test cases of all the routines. The file "mars_rover_vm.scad" takes some of the interesting parts from the inspiring mars rover project, and turns them into parts appropriate for usage in the openscad VM. The most complex object 'camera' shows how to nest CSG operations as well as primitive parts.

1) Download the openscad_vm.scad file to your work environment
2) Construct some object using lots of []'s in your code
3) Rejoice! Note: As this version does not support polyhedron, nor the 2D primitives, it's a bit limited. But, those are fairly straightforward to add. One very interesting side effect is that you can use the OpenScad_VM representation of an object as a transport mechanism!! That realization is sinking in for me and simplifying my life.

description.text: It's an away mission! They're compatible with those plastic figures you find for cheap in toy stores! It's Star Trek! I don't usually fanboy out like this, but I've been watching a lot of Star Trek lately (like, all of it.) We've been finding ways to play Wayfarer Tactics (the tabletop rules we're currently Kickstarting) on the cheap, and we turned our attention to to bags of plastic army men, pirates, knights, et cetera that you find in toy stores. All together, along with some 6-sided dice, a couple of decks of playing cards, and some floor space, you can have an awful lot of fun (we call this "$20 Tactics.") I got pretty interested in the idea of making low-res, easy-print models compatible with those kinds of toys, and I figured, hey, why not Star Trek? Each of these models (aside from the Guardian) takes about 30 minutes to print. I've had mixed results with the support materials, so if any of you are able to make more efficient supports, let me know, and I'd love to try printing/posting your version. Anyway, enjoy, and live long and prosper and stuff! (*model shown with Toysmith Soldier, Skeleton, and Pirate for scale reference.)

description.text:
After building Catastrophe's fantastic little Skeleton 3D printer , there was 1 thing about the printer that didn't work to my satisfaction: the extruder.
It works perfectly wel for PLA but for ABS it jammed regularly.
This is because ABS is both softer and more slippery and the extruder was designed and tested only for PLA by its designer.
I asked one of my best friends , and retired teacher in design with Inventor, to help redesign and draw in inventor a new extruder.This one should be based on a Gregs-Wade extruder, and placed on a adapted X-Y carriage. We also added a 30mm fan to cool the J-head.
The long screw, next to the J-Head in the drawing, serves as a support, to atach the wires for the heater cartridge and the thermistor with tie-raps.
The gears used are the standard Wade Big and Wade Small from the REPRAP wiki page of the Prusa Mendel i2, but we changed the gears a little bit to make them more solid. I'll add them to be complete.

I also added the STEP files , so you can adapt if needed.

Info update: The printer will only be made to print in PLA (and HDPE when we get a filastruder). it will have a water-cooled build plate, and possibly even a refrigerated build chamber. So, no ABS. Update: Made a more easily printed carriage quarter piece. Sad update: The printer idea that I spent so long developing has been calmed down to something practical. The designs here are probably better for a CNC, and the modular carriage-insert mounting design could be used for toolhead swapping. The printer itself will end up just being a MegaPrusa i3 with NEMA 23 adapters. Because the MegaPrusa... well, it is a little underpowered. I'll see what I can do.

I have found a practical use for the ABS slurry we use on our HBP's. Recently, it became necessary for me to resurrect my 20 year old power washer for a home project. The trouble is that it had been sitting for over 10 years, and among other things, the metal gas tank had rusted out somewhat.

I took the tank to my workplace, where we happen to have a sandblaster, and used that to clean all the rust from the (inside) bottom of the tank. In doing so, I created several pinholes where the metal was too thin. After cleaning it out, I brazed the larger holes where I could reach them, but due to the nature of the tanks design, there were several I could not reach. No problem! First I rinsed it thoroughly with acetone, blew it out with compressed air, made sure it was completely clean and dry inside. Then I took the ABS slurry for my Thing-O-Matic, and poured about 1/4 cup or so into the tank. The slurry was about the consistency of good thick gravy. I sloshed it around in the tank to cover all areas, suspended it over a heat lamp for about an hour, and bingo! the tank doesn't leak at all! Oh, I shoud mention that I also made sure that there was no slurry in the threaded fitting where the supply line/filter attaches at the bottom of the tank. I just dabbed it out with a piece of paper towel while the slurry was still wet. That was about 2 weeks ago, have put several tanks of fuel through it so far, still bone dry on the outside. Hope this info helps someone out there somewhere.....

description.text: The server room / 3d printer room needed organizing ;) I use finishing tools to clean up models before post processing, and needed a place to store these tools. The finishing tool rack can accomidate my rasps and the sidecar can hold tweezers and brass brushes for cleaning the nozzles on my printer. I designed the top slots to fit specifically the rasp set I have from Harbor Freight. the model is pretty much ready. if you want to use glue, you can print it now and use it as is. I am working on making a taller sidecar and an adjustment to the 'shelves' which the slots will sit on. I think its good measure to use glue, and will probably continue to recommend that as part of the process

What you need:  Gorilla Glue(or your favorite), a 3d printer.  
This worked best for me in PLA and I am running Octoprint on a Pi for my print server and doing all slicing in Simplify 3d.  I also passed all parts through netfabb to be on the safe side.  
The top slots are designed to fit directly over the basis model, you may need a little gorilla glue to prevent the slots from getting off balance when the tools are in place.  I glued the one in the photos and its set in about 8 hours. I left it overnight and it worked well.  
The sidecar connects as shown in the pictures, just set it gently and it fits together like the pieces of a puzzle.   You can print two sidecars, right now there is one in the photo.
